<br>
I never played UO, so I'll skip that.<br>
<br>
First of all, what do you mean by...<br>
3. Community(Actually getting rewarded for being nice, who'da thunk it?!)<br>
<br>
Personal EQ Cons:<br>
1. Camping (this guy is a rare spawn and he has a place holder, so I've been here since early January waiting on him for this Uber Lewt)<br>
2. Expansions (though in some ways expansions are very cool, they give you the opportunity to do new things, but in general they just make the game more expensive and totally shift the balance of in game items.... oh you are wearing Kunark Armor... why bother?<br>
3.  CORPSE RETRIEVAL!!! This is one of the dumbest ideas I've ever seen.  The idea that when you die you leave some lifeless shell of yourself that keeps all your gear on it and then you can go drag it around a zone like a your own little red wagon till you can find a cleric to "rez" you. Tho you aren't even being rezzed... you are alive!  You are just having them cast "Regain XP."<br>
4. Personally I don't think the new graphics are very good. They are better than the old ones but they are incredibly exaggerated and cartoonish, not to mention your point about the ridiculous computer requirements.<br>
5. All you get to do is kill mobs for either XP, or loot. You work to get the highest level so you can get the best spells (which you have to buy or loot) just so you can kill the big mobs so you can get the Uber Gear...<br>
6. Tradeskills are basically only good for doing parts of Quests. The stuff that drops in the game is so vastly superior to the stuff you can make with Tradeskills that there really isn't a point.<br>
7. monster level vs. player level - Something that cons "even" to you will totally kick your ass... unless maybe you have all of the uber lewtz.<br>
<br>
AO- <br>
The "bugs" to which you refer are not such a major part of the game anymore, at least not when last I played it. They've drastically fixed the game. When I first played it, it was almost unplayable, but when last I played it was pretty smooth.  <br>
<br>
You are right about there not really being a lot of point to gathering equipment, you need the stuff, or you are gonna die, but when you do get it, its not very good for your level and you level so fast it almost instantly needs replacing.<br>
<br>
There really is nothing quite as cool as being a "pet caster" but having a giant robot.<br>
<br>
DAOC-<br>
Though High end is mostly PVP, its not just PVP. Its Realm Versus Realm... So you and all your buddies versus them and all theirs... not just me versus you. Plus its not just about killing players.  You get to take keeps.  With the use of siege equipment (catapults, ballistas, battering rams), siege a keep, whack the guards and claim the keep. Having keeps benefits your realm by giving xp bonuses for killing mobs near the keep (even more if your guild or an alliance guild has claimed the keep). Also having more keeps than the other realms gives you access to a dungeon called Darkness Falls, which is both PVE and RVR. But.... there are also a lot of high end encounters, the so called "epic quests" which progress from level 10 to level 50 can get quite difficult at higher levels, requiring more than one group to defeat the end mobs (but the ones from about 10-35 are do-able solo or with just a friend or two). That is just an example though, there are many high end monsters that are just out there for multiple groups to go whack to get some phat lewtz.<br>
<br>
Pros for me:<br>
1. No corspe retrieval, see EQ portion for my hatred of corpse retrieval.<br>
2. Everyone gets a sprint skill, which when activated makes you run faster than most mobs in the game. Only wolves and horses (that I've seen) can run as fast as you while sprinting, so you can escape combats you don't wanna be in, without a spell effect on you.<br>
3. Tradeskills can be used to make equipment as good, or even better than the stuff dropped in game. <br>
4. Equipment doesn't make the character. You don't have to buy spells. So the only thing that decides what spells you have is how you chose to Specialize, not how much cash you had and if someone happened to be selling that awesome rare spell for only 83,000 K!<br>
5. Quests. Once you do the quest, its done. You can't do it again. And once you find the thing you gotta kill and you kill it, it ALWAYS drops the thing you need for your quest. No camping or farming required. I have never had to wait more than an hour or two for a quest monster to show up. Another cool thing is that for some quests, like your "epic quests" you actually trigger the monsters spawn.  My Armsmen had a quest dealing with the lost amulet of a long dead Roman Centurion, when I went to the spot, equipped the amulet, lightning started flashing and striking the columns nearby, and the guy spawned in a full run right at me. Of course Dave crapped his pants.<br>
6. The Classes are different. Though Albion has a lot of the classes that closely resemble the standard idea of Fantasy MMORPG... cleric, fighter, bard, paladin... every realms classes are completely different from one another. Even the fighters from different realms gain access to weaponry and skills not possessed by the other realms.  This, coupled with the awesome scenery, gives every realm a rich and very distinct style.<br>
7. Not as many minor annoyances, Don't need to buy food, no backpacks, don't need to go to a bank to get your money changed, money doesnt weigh anything, and having a few plat means you are a real rich mofo, and thats not even the highest money denomination.<br>
8. I've NEVER been in a group where if something dropped, they wanted to keep it, instead of giving it to the person who could most use it.  Heck, I've had people who were just running by give me things. And I've had groups give me stuff that dropped just because it was useable by my class, even though I said I didn't need it.<br>
9. Eight person groups.<br>
10. One time drops.  This guy has an item that no matter what, the first time you kill him (providing you are the right class and level to use the item) he drops it, and not on the ground, but straight in your inventory.<br>
11. One of my favorite things... Combat styles. Specializing in certain weapons gives you the ability to use different combat styles. It gives the fighters something to do  in combat other than hit taunt and kick.  Some styles require that you block first, others require you attack from the side or rear. So you actually have to do stuff as a tank.<br>
<br>
